the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baron Hugh de Corona was born in 1200, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Lucy before 1220, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in June 1291, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1200–June 1291":"1200–juuni 1291","–Female":"Surnud","1220–1260":"1220–1260","1200–1291":"1200–1291","June 1291":"juuni 1291","1200":"1200","before 1220":"enne 1220","1220":"1220","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Adlington, Cheshire, England":"Adlington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe",",Cheshire,England.":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–June 1291":"1200–kesäkuu 1291","–Female":"Kuollut","1220–1260":"1220–1260","1200–1291":"1200–1291","June 1291":"kesäkuu 1291","1200":"1200","before 1220":"ennen vuotta 1220","1220":"1220","1260":"1260","1291":"1291","Adlington, Cheshire, England":"Adlington, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Europe":"Europe",",Cheshire,England.":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1200–June 1291":"1200–juin 1291",